[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] JavaScript **`Date`** objects represent a single moment in time in a platform-independent format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date` objects encapsulate an integral number that represents milliseconds since the midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC (the *epoch*).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] A JavaScript date is fundamentally specified as the time in milliseconds that has elapsed since the epoch, which is defined as the midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC (equivalent to the UNIX epoch).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] This timestamp is *timezone-agnostic* and uniquely defines an instant in history.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The maximum timestamp representable by a `Date` object is slightly smaller than the maximum safe integer (`Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`, which is 9,007,199,254,740,991).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] This is the range from April 20, 271821 BC to September 13, 275760 AD.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Any attempt to represent a time outside this range results in the `Date` object holding a timestamp value of `NaN`, which is an "Invalid Date".
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] A date is represented internally as a single number, the *timestamp*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] When interacting with it, the timestamp needs to be interpreted as a structured date-and-time representation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] There are always two ways to interpret a timestamp: as a local time or as a Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the global standard time defined by the World Time Standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The local timezone is not stored in the date object, but is determined by the host environment (user's device).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The `getTimezoneOffset()` method returns the difference between UTC and the local time in minutes.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Note that the timezone offset does not only depend on the current timezone, but also on the time represented by the `Date` object, because of daylight saving time and historical changes.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] In essence, the timezone offset is the offset from UTC time, at the time represented by the `Date` object and at the location of the host environment.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] There are two groups of `Date` methods: one group gets and sets various date components by interpreting the timestamp as a local time, while the other uses UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The `Date()` constructor can be called with two or more arguments, in which case they are interpreted as the year, month, day, hour, minute, second, and millisecond, respectively, in local time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date.UTC()` works similarly, but it interprets the components as UTC time and also accepts a single argument representing the year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] When a segment overflows or underflows its expected range, it usually "carries over to" or "borrows from" the higher segment.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] For example, if the month is set to 12 (months are zero-based, so December is 11), it becomes the January of the next year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] If the day of month is set to 0, it becomes the last day of the previous month.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] This also applies to dates specified with the date time string format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] When attempting to set the local time to a time falling within an offset transition (usually daylight saving time), the exact time is derived using the same behavior as `Temporal`'s `disambiguation: "compatible"` option.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] That is, if the local time corresponds to two instants, the earlier one is chosen; if the local time does not exist (there is a gap), we go forward by the gap duration.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] There are many ways to format a date as a string.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The JavaScript specification only specifies one format to be universally supported: the *date time string format*, a simplification of the ISO 8601 calendar date extended format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] When the time zone offset is absent, **date-only forms are interpreted as a UTC time and date-time forms are interpreted as a local time.** The interpretation as a UTC time is due to a historical spec error that was not consistent with ISO 8601 but could not be changed due to web compatibility.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] See Broken Parser – A Web Reality Issue.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date.parse()` and the `Date()` constructor both accept strings in the date time string format as input.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Furthermore, implementations are allowed to support other date formats when the input fails to match this format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The `toISOString()` method returns a string representation of the date in the date time string format, with the time zone offset always set to `Z` (UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Non-standard strings can be parsed in any way as desired by the implementation, including the time zone — most implementations use the local time zone by default.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Implementations are not required to return invalid date for out-of-bounds date components, although they usually do.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] A string may have in-bounds date components (with the bounds defined above), but does not represent a date in reality (for example, "February 30").
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] Implementations behave inconsistently in this case.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] The `Date.parse()` page offers more examples about these non-standard cases.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-date] See the Formats of `toString` method return values section for examples.
