[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The **`Intl`** namespace object contains several constructors as well as functionality common to the internationalization constructors and other language sensitive functions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Collectively, they comprise the ECMAScript Internationalization API, which provides language sensitive string comparison, number formatting, date and time formatting, and more.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Unlike most global objects, `Intl` is not a constructor.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `Intl` object as a function.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] All properties and methods of `Intl` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The `locales` argument is used to determine the locale used in a given operation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The JavaScript implementation examines `locales`, and then computes a locale it understands that comes closest to satisfying the expressed preference.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] In the latter two cases, the actual locale used is the best-supported locale determined by locale negotiation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is not a string or an object, a `TypeError` is thrown.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is a string that's syntactically invalid, a `RangeError` is thrown.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If a locale identifier is well-formed but the implementation doesn't recognize it, it is ignored and the next locale in the list is considered, eventually falling back to the system's locale.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] However, you shouldn't rely on a particular locale name being ignored, because the implementation may add data for any locale in the future.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] For example, `new Intl.DateTimeFormat("default")` uses the implementation's default locale only because `"default"` is syntactically valid but not recognized as any locale.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Each subtag and sequence are separated by hyphens.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Locale identifiers are case-insensitive ASCII.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] However, it's conventional to use title case (the first letter is capitalized, successive letters are lower case) for script subtags, upper case for region subtags, and lower case for everything else.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Subtags identifying languages, scripts, regions (including countries), and (rarely used) variants are registered in the IANA Language Subtag Registry.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] This registry is periodically updated over time, and implementations may not always be up to date, so don't rely too much on subtags being universally supported.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] BCP 47 extension sequences consist of a single digit or letter (other than `"x"`) and one or more two- to eight-letter or digit subtags separated by hyphens.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Only one sequence is permitted for each digit or letter: `"de-a-foo-a-foo"` is invalid.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] BCP 47 extension subtags are defined in the Unicode CLDR Project.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Finally, a private-use extension sequence using the letter `"x"` may appear, followed by one or more one- to eight-letter or digit subtags separated by hyphens.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] This allows applications to encode information for their own private use, that will be ignored by all `Intl` operations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The `options` argument must be an object with properties that vary between constructors and functions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If the `options` argument is not provided or is undefined, default values are used for all properties.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] One property is supported by all language sensitive constructors and functions: The `localeMatcher` property, whose value must be a string `"lookup"` or `"best fit"` and which selects one of the locale matching algorithms described below.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The list of locales specified by the `locales` argument, after Unicode extensions have been removed from them, is interpreted as a prioritized request from the application.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The runtime compares it against the locales it has available and picks the best one available.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Two matching algorithms exist: the `"lookup"` matcher follows the Lookup algorithm specified in BCP 47; the `"best fit"` matcher lets the runtime provide a locale that's at least, but possibly more, suited for the request than the result of the Lookup algorithm.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If the application doesn't provide a `locales` argument, or the runtime doesn't have a locale that matches the request, then the runtime's default locale is used.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The matcher can be selected using a property of the `options` argument (see below).
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] If the selected locale identifier had a Unicode extension sequence, that extension is now used to customize the constructed object or the behavior of the function.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Each constructor or function supports only a subset of the keys defined for the Unicode extension, and the supported values often depend on the locale identifier.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] For example, the `"co"` key (collation) is only supported by `Intl.Collator`, and its `"phonebk"` value is only supported for German.
