[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl"`.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Returns a sorted array containing the supported unique calendar, collation, currency, numbering systems, or unit values supported by the implementation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] Alternatively, the `navigator.languages` property provides a sorted list of the user's preferred languages.
[src:dayjs-datetime/global-objects-intl] This list can be passed directly to the `Intl` constructors to implement preference-based fallback selection of locales.
[src:dayjs-datetime/installation] Day.js was designed to work both in the browser and in Node.js.
[src:dayjs-datetime/installation] All code should work in both of these environments, and all unit tests are run in both of these environments.
[src:dayjs-datetime/installation] Currently the following browsers are used for the ci system: Chrome on Windows XP, IE 8, 9, and 10 on Windows 7, IE 11 on Windows 10, latest Firefox on Linux, and latest Safari on OSX 10.8 and 10.11.
[src:dayjs-datetime/installation] If you want to try the sample codes, just open your browser's console and enter them.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601 applies to these representations and formats: dates, in the Gregorian calendar (including the proleptic Gregorian calendar); times, based on the 24-hour timekeeping system, with optional UTC offset, time intervals, and combinations thereof.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The standard does not assign specific meaning to any element of the dates/times represented: the meaning of any element depends on the context of its use.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Dates and times represented cannot use words that do not have a specified numerical meaning within the standard (thus excluding names of years in the Chinese calendar), or that do not use computer characters (excludes images or sounds).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] In representations that adhere to the ISO 8601 interchange standard, dates and times are arranged such that the greatest temporal term (typically a year) is placed at the left and each successively lesser term is placed to the right of the previous term.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The first edition of the ISO 8601 standard was published as *ISO 8601:1988* in June 1988.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] All editions and parts of ISO 8601 and its predecessors were prepared by, and are under the direct responsibility of, ISO Technical Committee TC 154.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Issued in February 2019, the fourth revision of the standard, ISO 8601-1:2019, represents slightly updated contents of the previous ISO 8601:2004 standard, but is now the first of two parts.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It defines various extensions such as uncertainties or parts of the Extended Date/Time Format (EDTF).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] An amendment to ISO 8601-1 was published in October 2022 featuring minor technical clarifications and attempts to remove ambiguities in definitions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The most significant change, however, was the reintroduction of the "24:00:00" format to refer to the instant at the *end* of a calendar day.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] An amendment to ISO 8601-2 was published in January 2025.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The standard uses the Gregorian calendar, which "serves as an international standard for civil use".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601 allows Gregorian dates from the introduction of the calendar on 15 October 1582.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For earlier (pre-Gregorian) dates, the calendar may be extended before its introduction (the proleptic Gregorian calendar) by explicit agreement of the parties involved.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Such proleptic dates may not be adjusted to reconcile them with Julian dates.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601 prescribes, as a minimum, a four-digit year [YYYY] to avoid the year 2000 problem.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It therefore represents years from 0000 to 9999, year 0000 being equal to 1 BC and all others AD, similar to astronomical year numbering.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] However, years before 1583 (the first full year following the introduction of the Gregorian calendar) are not automatically allowed by the standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Instead, the standard states that "values in the range [0000] through [1582] shall only be used by mutual agreement of the partners in information interchange".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] To represent years before 0000 or after 9999, the standard also permits the expansion of the year representation but only by prior agreement between the sender and the receiver.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] An expanded year representation [±YYYYY] must have an agreed-upon number of extra year digits beyond the four-digit minimum, and it must be prefixed with a + or - sign instead of the more common AD/BC (or CE/BCE) notation; by convention 1 BC is labelled +0000, 2 BC is labeled -0001, and so on.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Calendar date representations are in the form shown in the adjacent box. [YYYY] indicates a four-digit year, 0000 through 9999. [MM] indicates a two-digit month of the year, 01 through 12. [DD] indicates a two-digit day of that month, 01 through 31.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, "5 April 1981" may be represented as either "1981-04-05" in the *extended format* or "19810405" in the *basic format*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The standard also allows for calendar dates to be written with reduced precision.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] One may simply write "1981" to refer to that year, "198" to refer to the decade from 1980 to 1989 inclusive, or "19" to refer to the century from 1900 to 1999 inclusive.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Although the standard allows both the "YYYY-MM-DD" and YYYYMMDD formats for complete calendar date representations, if the day [DD] is omitted then only the YYYY-MM format is allowed.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] By disallowing dates of the form YYYYMM, the standard avoids confusion with the truncated representation YYMMDD (still often used).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The 2000 version also allowed writing the truncation "--04-05" to mean "April 5" but the 2004 version does not allow omitting the year when a month is present.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] As a consequence, if 1 January is on a Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday, it is in week 01.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If 1 January is on a Friday, Saturday or Sunday, it is in week 52 or 53 of the previous year (there is no week 00).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] 28 December is always in the last week of its year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The week number can be described by counting the Thursdays: Week 12 contains the 12th Thursday of the year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The *ISO week-numbering year* starts at the first day (Monday) of week 01 and ends at the Sunday before the new ISO year (hence without overlap or gap).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The first ISO week of a year may have up to three days that are actually in the Gregorian calendar year that is ending; if three, they are Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Similarly, the last ISO week of a year may have up to three days that are actually in the Gregorian calendar year that is starting; if three, they are Friday, Saturday, and Sunday.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The Thursday of each ISO week is always in the Gregorian calendar year denoted by the ISO week-numbering year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] An *ordinal date* is an ordinal format for the multiples of a day elapsed since the start of year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It is represented as "YYYY-DDD" (or YYYYDDD), where [YYYY] indicates a year and [DDD] is the "day of year", from 001 through 365 (366 in leap years).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This simple form is preferable for occasions when the arbitrary nature of week and month definitions are more of an impediment than an aid, for instance, when comparing dates from different calendars.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This format is used with simple hardware systems that have a need for a date system, but where including full calendar calculation software may be a significant nuisance.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Earlier versions omitted the T (representing time) in both formats.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] So a time might appear as either "T134730" in the *basic format* or "T13:47:30" in the *extended format*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601-1:2019 allows the T to be omitted in the extended format, as in "13:47:30", but only allows the T to be omitted in the basic format when there is no risk of confusion with date expressions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] As of ISO 8601-1:2019/Amd 1:2022, "00:00:00" may be used to refer to *midnight* corresponding to the instant at the beginning of a calendar day; and "24:00:00" to refer to midnight corresponding to the instant at the end of a calendar day.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601-1:2019 as originally published removed "24:00:00" as a representation for the end of day although it had been permitted in earlier versions of the standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A decimal fraction may be added to the lowest order time element present in any of these representations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A decimal mark, either a comma or a dot on the baseline, is used as a separator between the time element and its fraction.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] There is no limit on the number of decimal places for the decimal fraction.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] However, the number of decimal places needs to be agreed to by the communicating parties.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, in Microsoft SQL Server, the precision of a decimal fraction is 3 for a DATETIME, i.e., "yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm:ss[.mmm]".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Time zones in ISO 8601 are represented as local time (with the location unspecified), as UTC, or as an offset from UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If no UTC relation information is given with a time representation, the time is assumed to be in local time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] While it *may* be safe to assume local time when communicating in the same time zone, it is ambiguous when used in communicating across different time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Even within a single geographic time zone, some local times will be ambiguous if the region observes daylight saving time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It is usually preferable to indicate a time zone (zone designator) using the standard's notation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If the time is in UTC, add a *Z* directly after the time without a space.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] *Z* is the zone designator for the zero UTC offset.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The *Z* suffix in the ISO 8601 time representation is sometimes referred to as "Zulu time" or "Zulu meridian" because the same letter is used to designate the Zulu time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] However, the ACP 121 standard that defines the list of military time zones makes no mention of UTC and derives the "Zulu time" from the Greenwich Mean Time which was formerly used as the international civil time standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] *GMT* is no longer precisely defined by the scientific community and can refer to either UTC or UT1 depending on context.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The UTC offset is appended directly to the time instead of "Z" suffix above; other nautical time zone letters are not used.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The offset is applied to UTC to get the civil time in the designated time zone in the format '±[hh]:[mm]', '±[hh][mm]', or '±[hh]'.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A negative UTC offset describes a time zone west of the prime meridian where the civil time is behind UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] So the zone designation for New York (on standard time) would be "−05:00", "−0500", or "−05".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Conversely, a positive UTC offset describes a time zone east of the prime meridian where the civil time is ahead of UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A time zone where the civil time coincides with UTC is always designated as positive, though the offset is zero (see related specifications below).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] So the zone designation for London (on standard time) would be "+00:00", "+0000", or "+00".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] See List of UTC offsets for other UTC offsets.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It is not permitted to state a zero value time offset with a negative sign, as "−00:00", "−0000", or "−00".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The section dictating sign usage states that a plus sign must be used for a positive or zero value, and a minus sign for a negative value.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A plus-minus-sign (±) may also be used if it is available.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Contrary to this rule, RFC 3339, which is otherwise a profile of ISO 8601, permits the use of "−00" with the same denotation as "+00" but a differing connotation: an unknown UTC offset.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] To represent a negative offset, ISO 8601 specifies using a minus sign (−).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If the interchange character set is limited and does not have a minus sign character, then the hyphen-minus should be used (-).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ASCII does not have a minus sign, so its hyphen-minus character (code 4510) would be used.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If the character set has a minus sign, such as U+2212 − MINUS SIGN in Unicode, then that character should be used.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The HTML character entity invocation for − is `&minus;`.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601-2:2019 allows for general durations for time offsets.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, more precision can be added to the time offset with the format '<time>±[hh]:[mm]:[ss].[sss]' or '<time>±[n]H[n]M[n]S' as below.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A single point in time can be represented by concatenating a complete date expression, the letter *"T"* as a delimiter, and a valid time expression.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] In ISO 8601:2004 it was permitted to omit the *"T"* character by mutual agreement as in "200704051430", but this provision was removed in ISO 8601-1:2019.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Separating date and time parts with other characters such as space is not allowed in ISO 8601, but allowed in its profile RFC 3339.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If a time zone designator is required, it follows the combined date and time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Either basic or extended formats may be used, but both date and time must use the same format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The date expression may be calendar, week, or ordinal, and must use a complete representation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The time may be represented using a specified reduced precision format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Durations define the amount of intervening time in a time interval and are represented by the format P[n]Y[n]M[n]DT[n]H[n]M[n]S or P[n]W as shown on the aside.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] In these representations, the [n] is replaced by the value for each of the date and time elements that follow the [n].
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Leading zeros are not required, but the maximum number of digits for each element should be agreed to by the communicating parties.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The capital letters *P*, *Y*, *M*, *W*, *D*, *T*, *H*, *M*, and *S* are designators for each of the date and time elements and are not replaced.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, "P3Y6M4DT12H30M5S" represents a duration of "three years, six months, four days, twelve hours, thirty minutes, and five seconds".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Date and time elements including their designator may be omitted if their value is zero, and lower-order elements may also be omitted for reduced precision.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, "P23DT23H" and "P4Y" are both acceptable duration representations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] However, at least one element must be present, thus "P" is not a valid representation for a duration of 0 seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] "PT0S" or "P0D", however, are both valid and represent the same duration.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] To resolve ambiguity, "P1M" is a one-month duration and "PT1M" is a one-minute duration (note the time designator, T, that precedes the time value).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The smallest value used may also have a decimal fraction, as in "P0.5Y" to indicate half a year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This decimal fraction may be specified with either a comma or a full stop, as in "P0,5Y" or "P0.5Y".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The standard does not prohibit date and time values in a duration representation from exceeding their "carry over points" except as noted below.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Thus, "PT36H" could be used as well as "P1DT12H" for representing the same duration.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] But keep in mind that "PT36H" is not the same as "P1DT12H" when switching to or from daylight saving time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Alternatively, a format for duration based on combined date and time representations may be used by agreement between the communicating parties either in the basic format PYYYYMMDDThhmmss or in the extended format P[YYYY]-[MM]-[DD]T[hh]:[mm]:[ss].
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] However, individual date and time values cannot exceed their moduli (e.g. a value of 13 for the month or 25 for the hour would not be permissible).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The standard describes a duration as part of time intervals, which are discussed in the next section.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The duration format on its own is ambiguous regarding the total number of days in a calendar year and calendar month.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The number of seconds in a calendar day is also ambiguous because of leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example "P1M" on its own could be 28, 29, 30, or 31 days.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] There is no ambiguity when used in a time interval.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The duration format (or a subset thereof) is widely used independent of time intervals, as with the Java 8 Duration class which supports a subset of the duration format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A time interval is the intervening time between two time points.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The amount of intervening time is expressed by a duration (as described in the previous section).
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The two time points (start and end) are expressed by either a combined date and time representation or just a date representation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Of these, the first three require two values separated by an *interval designator* which is usually a solidus (more commonly referred to as a forward slash "/").
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Section 3.2.6 of ISO 8601-1:2019 notes that "A solidus may be replaced by a double hyphen ["--"] by mutual agreement of the communicating partners", and previous versions used notations like "2000--2002".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Use of a double hyphen instead of a solidus allows inclusion in computer filenames; in common operating systems, a solidus is a reserved character and is not allowed in a filename.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For <start>/<end> expressions, if any elements are missing from the end value, they are assumed to be the same as for the start value including the time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This feature of the standard allows for concise representations of time intervals.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If greater precision is desirable to represent the time interval, then more time elements can be added to the representation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] To explicitly include all of the start and end dates, the interval would be represented as "2007-11-13T00:00/16T00:00".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Repeating intervals are specified in clause "4.5 Recurring time interval".
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] They are formed by adding "R[n]/" to the beginning of an interval expression, where *R* is used as the letter itself and [n] is replaced by the number of repetitions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Leaving out the value for [n] or specifying a value of -1, means an unbounded number of repetitions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] A value of 0 for [n] means the interval is not repeated.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If the interval specifies the start (forms 1 and 2 above), then this is the start of the repeating interval.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] If the interval specifies the end but not the start (form 3 above), then this is the end of the repeating interval.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It is based on syntax from iCalendar and shared by IETF RFC 5545.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601:2000 allowed truncation (by agreement), where leading components of a date or time are omitted.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Notably, this allowed two-digit years to be used as well as the ambiguous formats YY-MM-DD and YYMMDD.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This provision was removed in ISO 8601:2004.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The first and seventh examples given above omit the leading `-` for century.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Other formats have one leading `-` per omitted century, year, month, week, hour and minute as necessary to disambiguate the format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601-2:2019 defines a set of standardised extensions to the ISO 8601 date and time formats.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The EDTF is given as an example of a profile of ISO 8601 in Part 2.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It comes in three levels, where level 0 is a subset of Part 1 restricted to extended month–day notation, CCYY-MM-DD, similar to RFC 3339, and levels 1 and 2 build upon that.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] EDTF is mostly tailored to bibliographic and historiographic needs.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The EDTF features are described in the "Date and Time Extensions" section of ISO 8601-2:2019, and the profile itself is found as Annex A.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It is virtually identical to the prior specification pioneered by the US Library of Congress.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] On the Internet, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) uses the IETF standard based on ISO 8601 in defining a profile of the standard that restricts the supported date and time formats to reduce the chance of error and the complexity of software.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The very simple specification is based on a draft of the RFC 3339 mentioned below.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] ISO 8601 is referenced by several specifications, but the full range of options of ISO 8601 is not always used.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] For example, the various electronic program guide standards for TV, digital radio, etc. use several forms to describe points in time and durations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The ID3 audio meta-data specification also makes use of a subset of ISO 8601.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The X.690 encoding standard's GeneralizedTime makes use of another subset of ISO 8601.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] As of 2006, the ISO week date appears in its basic form on major brand commercial packaging in the United States.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Its appearance depended on the particular packaging, canning, or bottling plant more than any particular brand.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The format is particularly useful for quality assurance, so that production errors can be readily traced.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] IETF RFC 3339 defines a profile of ISO 8601 for use in Internet protocols and standards.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] It explicitly excludes durations and dates before the common era.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The more complex formats such as week numbers and ordinal days are not permitted.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] RFC 3339 deviates from ISO 8601 in allowing a zero time zone offset to be specified as "-00:00", which ISO 8601 forbids.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] RFC 3339 intends "-00:00" to carry the connotation that it is not stating a preferred time zone, whereas the conforming "+00:00" or any non-zero offset connotes that the offset being used is preferred.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This convention regarding "-00:00" is derived from earlier RFCs, such as RFC 2822 which uses it for timestamps in email headers.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] RFC 2822 made no claim that any part of its timestamp format conforms to ISO 8601, and so was free to use this convention without conflict.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Building upon the foundations of RFC 3339, the IETF introduced the Internet Extended Date/Time Format (IXDTF) in RFC 9557.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] This format extends the timestamp representation to include additional information such as an associated time zone name.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] The inclusion of time zone names is particularly useful for applications that need to account for events like daylight saving time transitions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/iso-8601] Furthermore, IXDTF maintains compatibility with pre-existing syntax for attaching time zone names to timestamps, providing a standardized and flexible approach to timestamp representation on the internet.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] A **time zone** is an area which observes a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Time zones tend to follow the boundaries between countries and their subdivisions instead of strictly following longitude, because it is convenient for areas in frequent communication to keep the same time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Each time zone is defined by a standard offset from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The offsets range from UTC−12:00 to UTC+14:00, and are usually a whole number of hours, but a few zones are offset by an additional 30 or 45 minutes, such as in India and Nepal.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Some areas in a time zone may use a different offset for part of the year, typically one hour ahead during spring and summer, a practice known as daylight saving time (DST).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In the table below, the locations that use daylight saving time are listed in their UTC offset when DST is *not* in effect.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] When DST is in effect, approximately during spring and summer, their UTC offset is increased by one hour (except for Lord Howe Island, where it is increased by 30 minutes).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, during the DST period, California observes UTC−07:00 and the United Kingdom observes UTC+01:00.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The apparent position of the Sun in the sky, and thus solar time, varies by location due to the spherical shape of the Earth.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This variation corresponds to four minutes of time for every degree of longitude; for example, when it is solar noon in London, it is about 10 minutes before solar noon in Bristol, which is about 2.5 degrees to the west.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Local solar time has been associated with civil timekeeping since the development of sundials; for example, c.1500 BC, an ancient Egyptian sundial was used to measure laborers' work hours.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In the 2nd century BC, Hipparchus developed a method to measure longitudinal distances by comparing local solar times when a lunar eclipse was simultaneously observed at two locations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The work of Hipparchus is lost, but is known from citations in Strabo's Geographica, c.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The Royal Observatory, Greenwich, founded in 1675, established Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), the mean solar time at that location, as an aid to mariners to determine longitude at sea, providing a standard reference time while each location in England kept a different time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In the 19th century, as transportation and telecommunications improved, it became increasingly inconvenient for each location to observe its own solar time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In November 1840, the British Great Western Railway started using GMT kept by portable chronometers.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This practice was soon adopted by other British railway companies and became known as **railway time**.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Around August 23, 1852, time signals were first transmitted by telegraph from the Royal Observatory.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] By 1855, 98% of Great Britain's public clocks were using GMT, but it was not made the island's legal time until August 2, 1880.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Some British clocks from this period have two minute hands, one for the local time and one for GMT.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] On November 2, 1868, the British Colony of New Zealand officially adopted a standard time to be observed throughout the colony.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] It was based on longitude 172°30′ east of Greenwich, or 11 hours 30 minutes ahead of GMT.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This standard was known as New Zealand Mean Time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Timekeeping on North American railroads in the 19th century was complex.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Each railroad used its own standard time, usually based on the local time of its headquarters or most important terminus, and the railroad's train schedules were published using its own time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Some junctions served by several railroads had a clock for each railroad, each showing a different time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Because of this, a number of accidents occurred when trains from different companies using the same tracks mistimed their passings.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Dowd proposed a system of hourly standard time zones for North American railroads, although he published nothing on the matter at that time and did not consult railroad officials until 1869.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In 1870, he proposed four ideal time zones having north–south borders, the first centered on Washington, D.C..
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] By 1872, the first was centered on the meridian 75° west of Greenwich, with natural borders such as sections of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Dowd's system was never accepted by North American railroads.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Cleveland Abbe, chief meteorologist at the United States Weather Bureau, divided the United States into four standard time zones for consistency among the weather stations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In 1879, he published a paper titled *Report on Standard Time*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In 1883, he convinced North American railroad companies to adopt his time-zone system.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In 1884, Britain, which had already adopted its own standard time system for England, Scotland, and Wales, helped gather international consent for global time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In time, the American government, influenced in part by Abbe's 1879 paper, adopted the time-zone system.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Allen, the editor of the *Traveler's Official Railway Guide*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The borders of its time zones ran through railroad stations, often in major cities.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, the border between its Eastern and Central time zones ran through Detroit, Buffalo, Pittsburgh, Atlanta, and Charleston.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] It was inaugurated on Sunday, November 18, 1883, also called "The Day of Two Noons", when each railroad station clock was reset as standard-time noon was reached within each time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The North American zones were named Intercolonial, Eastern, Central, Mountain, and Pacific.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Within a year 85% of all cities with populations over 10,000 (about 200 cities) were using standard time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The confusion of times came to an end when standard time zones were formally adopted by the U.S.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Congress in the Standard Time Act of March 19, 1918.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Italian mathematician Quirico Filopanti introduced the idea of a worldwide system of time zones in his book *Miranda!*, published in 1858.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] He proposed 24 hourly time zones, which he called "longitudinal days", the first centred on the meridian of Rome.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] He also proposed a universal time to be used in astronomy and telegraphy.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] However, his book attracted no attention until long after his death.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Scottish-born Canadian Sir Sandford Fleming proposed a worldwide system of time zones in 1876 - see Sandford Fleming § Inventor of worldwide standard time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The proposal divided the world into twenty-four time zones labeled A-Y (skipping J), each one covering 15 degrees of longitude.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] All clocks within each zone would be set to the same time as the others, but differed by one hour from those in the neighboring zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] He advocated his system at several international conferences, including the International Meridian Conference, where it received some consideration.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The system has not been directly adopted, but some maps divide the world into 24 time zones and assign letters to them, similarly to Fleming's system.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] By about 1900, almost all inhabited places on Earth had adopted a standard time zone, but only some of them used an hourly offset from GMT.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Many applied the time at a local astronomical observatory to an entire country, without any reference to GMT.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] It took many decades before all time zones were based on some standard offset from GMT or Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] By 1929, the majority of countries had adopted hourly time zones, though some countries such as Iran, India, Myanmar, and parts of Australia had time zones with a 30-minute offset.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Nepal was the last country to adopt a standard offset, shifting slightly to UTC+05:45 in 1986.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] All nations currently use standard time zones for secular purposes, but not all of them apply the concept as originally conceived.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Several countries and subdivisions use half-hour or quarter-hour deviations from standard time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The consequences, in some areas, can affect the lives of local citizens, and in extreme cases contribute to larger political issues, such as in the western reaches of China.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] ISO 8601 is a standard established by the International Organization for Standardization defining methods of representing dates and times in textual form, including specifications for representing time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] If a time is in UTC, a "Z" is added directly after the time without a separating space.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] "Z" is the zone designator for the zero UTC offset.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] UTC time is also known as "Zulu" time, since "Zulu" is a phonetic alphabet code word for the letter "Z".
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Offsets from UTC are written in the format ±hh:mm, ±hhmm, or ±hh (either hours ahead or behind UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, if the time being described is one hour ahead of UTC (such as the time in Germany during the winter), the zone designator would be "+01:00", "+0100", or simply "+01".
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This numeric representation of time zones is appended to local times in the same way that alphabetic time zone abbreviations (or "Z", as above) are appended.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The offset from UTC changes with daylight saving time, e.g. a time offset in Chicago, which is in the North American Central Time Zone, is "−06:00" for the winter (Central Standard Time) and "−05:00" for the summer (Central Daylight Time).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Time zones are often represented by alphabetic abbreviations such as "EST", "WST", and "CST", though these are not part of the international time and date standard ISO 8601.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Such designations can be ambiguous; for example, "CST" can mean (North American) Central Standard Time (UTC−06:00), Cuba Standard Time (UTC−05:00), or China Standard Time (UTC+08:00), and is also a widely used variant of ACST (Australian Central Standard Time, UTC+09:30).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] in which each side of the equation is equivalent to UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] "time in zone B" = "time in zone A" − "UTC offset for zone A" + "UTC offset for zone B".
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, the New York Stock Exchange opens at 09:30 (EST, UTC offset= −05:00).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] These calculations become more complicated near the time switch to or from daylight saving time, as the UTC offset for the area becomes a function of UTC time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The time differences may also result in different dates.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, when it is 22:00 on Monday in Egypt (UTC+02:00), it is 01:00 on Tuesday in Pakistan (UTC+05:00).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The table "Time of day by zone" gives an overview on the time relations between different zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Since the 1920s, a nautical standard time system has been in operation for ships on the high seas.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] As an ideal form of the terrestrial time zone system, nautical time zones consist of gores of 15° offset from GMT by a whole number of hours.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] A nautical date line follows the 180th meridian, bisecting one 15° gore into two 7.5° gores that differ from GMT by ±12 hours.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] However, in practice each ship may choose what time to observe at each location.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Ships may decide to adjust their clocks at a convenient time, usually at night, not exactly when they cross a certain longitude.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Some ships simply remain on the time of the departing port during the whole trip.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Ideal time zones, such as nautical time zones, are based on the mean solar time of a particular meridian in the middle of that zone with boundaries located 7.5 degrees east and west of the meridian.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In practice, however, many time zone boundaries are drawn much farther to the west, and some countries are located entirely outside their ideal time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, even though the Prime Meridian (0°) passes through Spain and France they use the mean solar time of 15 degrees east (Central European Time) rather than 0 degrees (Greenwich Mean Time).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] France previously used GMT, but was switched to CET (Central European Time) during the German occupation of the country during World War II and did not switch back after the war.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Similarly, prior to World War II, the Netherlands observed "Amsterdam Time", which was twenty minutes ahead of Greenwich Mean Time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] They were obliged to follow German time during the war, and kept it thereafter.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In the mid-1970s the Netherlands, as other European states, began observing daylight saving (summer) time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] One reason to draw time zone boundaries far to the west of their ideal meridians is to allow the more efficient use of afternoon sunlight.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Some of these locations also use daylight saving time, further increasing the difference to local solar time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] As a result, in summer, solar noon in the Spanish city of Vigo occurs at 14:41 clock time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This westernmost area of continental Spain never experiences sunset before 18:00 clock time, even in winter, despite lying 42 degrees north of the equator.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Near the summer solstice, Vigo has sunset times after 22:00, similar to those of Stockholm, which is in the same time zone and 17 degrees farther north.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Stockholm has much earlier sunrises, though.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In the United States, the reasons were more historical and business-related.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In Midwestern states, like Indiana and Michigan, those living in Indianapolis and Detroit wanted to be on the same time zone as New York City to simplify communications and transactions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] A more extreme example is Nome, Alaska, which is at 165°24′W longitude – just west of center of the idealized Samoa Time Zone (165°W).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Nevertheless, Nome observes Alaska Time (135°W) with DST so it is slightly more than two hours ahead of the sun in winter and over three in summer.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Kotzebue, Alaska, also near the same meridian but north of the Arctic Circle, has *two* sunsets on the same day in early August, one shortly after midnight at the start of the day, and the other shortly before midnight at the end of the day.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Consequently, in early May, in Kotzebue one day does not have sunset.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] China extends as far west as 73°E, but all parts of it use UTC+08:00 (120°E), so solar "noon" can occur as late as 15:00 in western portions of China such as Xinjiang.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The Afghanistan-China border marks the greatest terrestrial time zone difference on Earth, with a 3.5 hour difference between Afghanistan's UTC+4:30 and China's UTC+08:00.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] A visualization of the mismatch between clock time and solar time in different locations.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] In blue areas, clock time lags behind solar time; in red areas, the reverse is true.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The two are synchronized in the white areas.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Many countries, and sometimes just certain regions of countries, adopt daylight saving time (DST), also known as summer time, during part of the year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This typically involves advancing clocks by an hour near the start of spring and adjusting back in autumn ("spring forward", "fall back").
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Modern DST was first proposed in 1907 and was in widespread use in 1916 as a wartime measure aimed at conserving coal.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Despite controversy, many countries have used it off and on since then; details vary by location and change occasionally.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Countries around the equator usually do not observe daylight saving time, since the seasonal difference in sunlight there is minimal.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Many computer operating systems include the necessary support for working with many or all possible local times.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Internally, operating systems typically use UTC as their basic time-keeping standard and convert local times, including daylight savings time, to and from UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Web servers presenting web pages primarily for an audience in a single time zone or a limited range of time zones typically show times as a local time, perhaps with UTC time in brackets.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] More internationally oriented websites may show times in UTC only or using an arbitrary time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, the international English-language version of CNN includes GMT and Hong Kong Time, whereas the US version shows Eastern Time.US Eastern Time and Pacific Time are also used fairly commonly on many US-based English-language websites with global readership.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The format is typically based in the W3C Note "datetime".
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Email systems and other messaging systems (IRC chat, etc.) time-stamp messages using UTC, or else include the sender's time zone as part of the message, allowing the receiving program to display the message's date and time of sending in the recipient's local time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Database records that include a time stamp typically use UTC, especially when the database is part of a system that spans multiple time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The use of local time for time-stamping records is not recommended for time zones that implement daylight saving time because once a year there is a one-hour period when local times are ambiguous.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Calendar systems nowadays usually tie their time stamps to UTC, and show them differently on computers that are in different time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] That works when having telephone or internet meetings.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] It works less well when travelling, because the calendar events are assumed to take place in the time zone the computer or smartphone was on when creating the event.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The event can be shown at the wrong time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] For example, if a Los Angeles resident visits New York and before the journey makes a calendar entry for the return flight at 9 am (which the computer assumes is Los Angeles time), the calendar entry will be at noon if taking the computer's new New York time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Calendaring software must also deal with daylight saving time (DST), usually done so calendar entries made before the shift are shown the same after it.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] If, for political reasons, the begin and end dates of daylight saving time are changed, calendar entries should stay the same in local time, even though they may shift in UTC time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Unix-like systems, including Linux and macOS, keep system time in Unix time format, representing the number of seconds that have elapsed since 00:00:00 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) on Thursday, January 1, 1970, excluding leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Unix time is usually converted to local time when displayed to the user, and times specified by the user in local time are converted to Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The conversion takes into account the time zone and daylight saving time rules; by default the time zone and daylight saving time rules are set up when the system is configured, though individual processes can specify time zones and daylight saving time rules using the *TZ* environment variable.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This allows users in multiple time zones, or in the same time zone but with different daylight saving time rules, to use the same computer, with their respective local times displayed correctly to each user.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Information about time zones and daylight saving time rules most commonly comes from the IANA time zone database.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Many systems, including anything using the GNU C Library, a C library based on the BSD C library, or the System V Release 4 C library, can make use of the IANA time zone database.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Windows-based computer systems prior to Windows 95 and Windows NT used local time, but Windows 95 and later, and Windows NT, base system time on UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] They allow a program to fetch the system time as UTC, represented as a year, month, day, hour, minute, second, and millisecond; Windows 95 and later, and Windows NT 3.5 and later, also allow the system time to be fetched as a count of 100 ns units since 1601-01-01 00:00:00 UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The system registry contains time zone information that includes the offset from UTC and rules that indicate the start and end dates for daylight saving in each zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Interaction with the user normally uses local time, and application software is able to calculate the time in various zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Terminal Servers allow remote computers to redirect their time zone settings to the Terminal Server so that users see the correct time for their time zone in their desktop/application sessions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Terminal Services uses the server base time on the Terminal Server and the client time zone information to calculate the time in the session.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] While most application software will use the underlying operating system for time zone and daylight saving time rule information, the Java Platform, from version 1.3.1, has maintained its own database of time zone and daylight saving time rule information, based on the IANA time zone database.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This database is updated whenever time zone or daylight saving time rules change.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Oracle provides an updater tool for this purpose.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] As an alternative to the information bundled with the Java Platform, programmers may choose to use the Joda-Time library.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This library includes its own data based on the IANA time zone database.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] As of Java 8 there is a new date and time API that can help with converting times.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Traditionally, there was very little in the way of time zone support for JavaScript.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Essentially the programmer had to extract the UTC offset by instantiating a time object, getting a GMT time from it, and differencing the two.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This does not provide a solution for more complex daylight saving variations, such as divergent DST directions between northern and southern hemispheres.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] ECMA-402, the standard on Internationalization API for JavaScript, provides ways of formatting Time Zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] However, due to size constraint, some implementations or distributions do not include it.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The DateTime object in Perl supports all entries in the IANA time zone database and includes the ability to get, set and convert between time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The DateTime objects and related functions have been compiled into the PHP core since 5.2.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] This includes the ability to get and set the default script time zone, and DateTime is aware of its own time zone internally.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] PHP.net provides extensive documentation on this.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] As noted there, the most current time zone database can be implemented via the PECL timezonedb.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The standard module datetime included with Python stores and operates on the time zone information class tzinfo.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The third party pytz module provides access to the full IANA time zone database.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Negated time zone offset in seconds is stored time.timezone and time.altzone attributes.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] From Python 3.9, the zoneinfo module introduces timezone management without need for third party module.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Each Smalltalk dialect comes with its own built-in classes for dates, times and timestamps, only a few of which implement the DateAndTime and Duration classes as specified by the ANSI Smalltalk Standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] VisualWorks provides a TimeZone class that supports up to two annually recurring offset transitions, which are assumed to apply to all years (same behavior as Windows time zones).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Squeak provides a Timezone class that does not support any offset transitions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Dolphin Smalltalk does not support time zones at all.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Orbiting spacecraft may experience many sunrises and sunsets, or none, in a 24-hour period.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Therefore, it is not possible to calibrate the time with respect to the Sun and still respect a 24-hour sleep/wake cycle.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] A common practice for space exploration is to use the Earth-based time of the launch site or mission control, synchronizing the sleeping cycles of the crew and controllers.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] The International Space Station normally uses Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Timekeeping on Mars can be more complex, since the planet has a solar day of approximately 24 hours and 40 minutes, known as a sol.
[src:dayjs-datetime/time-zone] Earth controllers for some Mars missions have synchronized their sleep/wake cycles with the Martian day, when specifically solar-powered rover activity occurs.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time originated as the system time of Unix operating systems.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] It has come to be widely used in other computer operating systems, file systems, programming languages, and databases.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In modern computing, values are sometimes stored with higher granularity, such as microseconds or nanoseconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is currently defined as the number of non-leap seconds which have passed since 00:00:00 UTC on Thursday, 1 January 1970, which is referred to as the *Unix epoch*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is typically encoded as a signed integer.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The Unix time 0 is exactly midnight UTC on 1 January 1970, with Unix time incrementing by 1 for every non-leap second after this.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] For example, 00:00:00 UTC on 1 January 1971 is represented in Unix time as 31536000.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Negative values, on systems that support them, indicate times before the Unix epoch, with the value decreasing by 1 for every non-leap second before the epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is sometimes referred to as *Epoch time*.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This can be misleading since Unix time is not the only time system based on an epoch and the Unix epoch is not the only epoch used by other time systems.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time differs from both Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and International Atomic Time (TAI) in its handling of leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] UTC includes leap seconds that adjust for the discrepancy between precise time, as measured by atomic clocks, and solar time, relating to the position of the earth in relation to the sun.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] International Atomic Time (TAI), in which every day is precisely 86400 seconds long, ignores solar time and gradually loses synchronization with the Earth's rotation as Earth slows at around 1.5 ms per day per century.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In Unix time, every day contains exactly 86400 seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Each leap second uses the timestamp of a second that immediately precedes or follows it.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] On a normal UTC day, which has a duration of 86400 seconds, the Unix time number changes in a continuous manner across midnight.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] When a leap second occurs, the UTC day is not exactly 86400 seconds long and the Unix time number (which always increases by exactly 86400 each day) experiences a discontinuity.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Leap seconds may be positive or negative.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] No negative leap second has ever been declared, but if one were to be, then at the end of a day with a negative leap second, the Unix time number would jump up by 1 to the start of the next day.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] During a positive leap second at the end of a day, which occurs about every year and a half on average, the Unix time number increases continuously into the next day during the leap second and then at the end of the leap second jumps back by 1 (returning to the start of the next day).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time numbers are repeated in the second immediately following a positive leap second.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In the theoretical case when a negative leap second occurs, no ambiguity is caused, but instead there is a range of Unix time numbers that do not refer to any point in UTC time at all.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A Unix clock is often implemented with a different type of positive leap second handling associated with the Network Time Protocol (NTP).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This yields a system that does not conform to the POSIX standard.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] See the section below concerning NTP for details.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] When dealing with periods that do not encompass a UTC leap second, the difference between two Unix time numbers is equal to the duration in seconds of the period between the corresponding points in time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This is a common computational technique.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] However, where leap seconds occur, such calculations give the wrong answer.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In applications where this level of accuracy is required, it is necessary to consult a table of leap seconds when dealing with Unix times, and it is often preferable to use a different time encoding that does not suffer from this problem.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A Unix time number is easily converted back into a UTC time by taking the quotient and modulus of the Unix time number, modulo 86400.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The quotient is the number of days since the epoch, and the modulus is the number of seconds since midnight UTC on that day.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] If given a Unix time number that is ambiguous due to a positive leap second, this algorithm interprets it as the time just after midnight.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] It never generates a time that is during a leap second.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] If given a Unix time number that is invalid due to a negative leap second, it generates an equally invalid UTC time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] If these conditions are significant, it is necessary to consult a table of leap seconds to detect them.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Commonly a Mills-style Unix clock is implemented with leap second handling not synchronous with the change of the Unix time number.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The time number initially decreases where a leap should have occurred, and then it leaps to the correct time 1 second after the leap.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This makes implementation easier, and is described by Mills' paper.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This can be decoded properly by paying attention to the leap second state variable, which unambiguously indicates whether the leap has been performed yet.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The state variable change is synchronous with the leap.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A similar situation arises with a negative leap second, where the second that is skipped is slightly too late.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Very briefly the system shows a nominally impossible time number, but this can be detected by the TIME_DEL state and corrected.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In this type of system the Unix time number violates POSIX around both types of leap second.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Collecting the leap second state variable along with the time number allows for unambiguous decoding, so the correct POSIX time number can be generated if desired, or the full UTC time can be stored in a more suitable format.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The decoding logic required to cope with this style of Unix clock would also correctly decode a hypothetical POSIX-conforming clock using the same interface.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This would be achieved by indicating the TIME_INS state during the entirety of an inserted leap second, then indicating TIME_WAIT during the entirety of the following second while repeating the seconds count.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This requires synchronous leap second handling.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This is probably the best way to express UTC time in Unix clock form, via a Unix interface, when the underlying clock is fundamentally untroubled by leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Another, much rarer, non-conforming variant of Unix time keeping involves incrementing the value for all seconds, including leap seconds; some Linux systems are configured this way.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Because TAI has no leap seconds, and every TAI day is exactly 86400 seconds long, this encoding is actually a pure linear count of seconds elapsed since 1970-01-01T00:00:10 TAI.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This makes time interval arithmetic much easier.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Time values from these systems do not suffer the ambiguity that strictly conforming POSIX systems or NTP-driven systems have.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In these systems it is necessary to consult a table of leap seconds to correctly convert between UTC and the pseudo-Unix-time representation.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This resembles the manner in which time zone tables must be consulted to convert to and from civil time; the IANA time zone database includes leap second information, and the sample code available from the same source uses that information to convert between TAI-based timestamps and local time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Conversion also runs into definitional problems prior to the 1972 commencement of the current form of UTC (see section UTC basis below).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This system, despite its superficial resemblance, is not Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] It encodes times with values that differ by several seconds from the POSIX time values.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A version of this system, in which the epoch was 1970-01-01T00:00:00 TAI rather than 1970-01-01T00:00:10 TAI, was proposed for inclusion in ISO C's `time.h`, but only the UTC part was accepted in 2011.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A `tai_clock` does, however, exist in C++20.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A Unix time number can be represented in any form capable of representing numbers.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In some applications the number is simply represented textually as a string of decimal digits, raising only trivial additional problems.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] However, certain binary representations of Unix times are particularly significant.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The Unix `time_t` data type that represents a point in time is, on many platforms, a signed integer, traditionally of 32 bits (but see below), directly encoding the Unix time number as described in the preceding section.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A signed 32-bit value covers about 68 years before and after the 1970-01-01 epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The minimum representable date is Friday 1901-12-13, and the maximum representable date is Tuesday 2038-01-19.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] One second after 2038-01-19T03:14:07Z this representation will overflow in what is known as the year 2038 problem.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] UUIDv7 encodes the Unix epoch timestamp (in milliseconds) in an unsigned 48-bit field.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This representation is valid until the year 10889.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] In some newer operating systems, `time_t` has been widened to 64 bits.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This expands the times representable to 292277264695 (292.3 billion) years in both directions, which is over twenty times the present age of the universe.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] There was originally some controversy over whether the Unix `time_t` should be signed or unsigned.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] If unsigned, its range in the future would be doubled, postponing the 32-bit overflow (by 68 years).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] However, it would then be incapable of representing times prior to the epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The consensus is for `time_t` to be signed, and this is the usual practice.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The software development platform for version 6 of the QNX operating system has an unsigned 32-bit `time_t`, though older releases used a signed type.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The POSIX and Open Group Unix specifications include the C standard library, which includes the time types and functions defined in the `<time.h>` header file.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The ISO C standard states that `time_t` must be an arithmetic type, but does not mandate any specific type or encoding for it.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] POSIX requires `time_t` to be an integer type, but does not mandate that it be signed or unsigned.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix has no tradition of directly representing non-integer Unix time numbers as binary fractions.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] These structures provide a decimal-based fixed-point data format, which is useful for some applications, and trivial to convert for others.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The present form of UTC, with leap seconds, is defined only starting from 1 January 1972.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Prior to 1961 there was no UTC, and prior to 1958 there was no widespread atomic timekeeping; in these eras, some approximation of GMT (based directly on the Earth's rotation) was used instead of an atomic timescale.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The precise definition of Unix time as an encoding of UTC is only uncontroversial when applied to the present form of UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The Unix epoch predating the start of this form of UTC does not affect its use in this era: the number of days from 1 January 1970 (the Unix epoch) to 1 January 1972 (the start of UTC) is not in question, and the number of days is all that is significant to Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The meaning of Unix time values below +63072000 (i.e., prior to 1 January 1972) is not precisely defined.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The basis of such Unix times is best understood to be an unspecified approximation of UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Computers of that era rarely had clocks set sufficiently accurately to provide meaningful sub-second timestamps in any case.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is not a suitable way to represent times prior to 1972 in applications requiring sub-second precision; such applications must, at least, define which form of UT or GMT they use.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] As of 2009, the possibility of ending the use of leap seconds in civil time is being considered.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] A likely means to execute this change is to define a new time scale, called *International Time*, that initially matches UTC but thereafter has no leap seconds, thus remaining at a constant offset from TAI.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] If this happens, it is likely that Unix time will be prospectively defined in terms of this new time scale, instead of UTC.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Uncertainty about whether this will occur makes prospective Unix time no less predictable than it already is: if UTC were simply to have no further leap seconds the result would be the same.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The earliest versions of Unix time had a 32-bit integer incrementing at a rate of 60 Hz, which was the rate of the system clock on the hardware of the early Unix systems.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Timestamps stored this way could only represent a range of a little over two and a quarter years.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The epoch being counted from was changed with Unix releases to prevent overflow, with midnight on 1 January 1971 and 1 January 1972 both being used as epochs during Unix's early development.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Early definitions of Unix time also lacked time zones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The current epoch of 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC was selected arbitrarily by Unix engineers because it was considered a convenient date to work with.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The precision was changed to count in seconds in order to avoid short-term overflow.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] When POSIX.1 was written, the question arose of how to precisely define `time_t` in the face of leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The POSIX committee considered whether Unix time should remain, as intended, a linear count of seconds since the epoch, at the expense of complexity in conversions with civil time or a representation of civil time, at the expense of inconsistency around leap seconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Computer clocks of the era were not sufficiently precisely set to form a precedent one way or the other.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The POSIX committee was swayed by arguments against complexity in the library functions, and firmly defined the Unix time in a simple manner in terms of the elements of UTC time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This definition was so simple that it did not even encompass the entire leap year rule of the Gregorian calendar, and would make 2100 a leap year.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The 2001 edition of POSIX.1 rectified the faulty leap year rule in the definition of Unix time, but retained the essential definition of Unix time as an encoding of UTC rather than a linear time scale.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Since the mid-1990s, computer clocks have been routinely set with sufficient precision for this to matter, and they have most commonly been set using the UTC-based definition of Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] This has resulted in considerable complexity in Unix implementations, and in the Network Time Protocol, to execute steps in the Unix time number whenever leap seconds occur.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is widely adopted in computing beyond its original application as the system time for Unix.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is available in almost all system programming APIs, including those provided by both Unix-based and non-Unix operating systems.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Almost all modern programming languages provide APIs for working with Unix time or converting them to another data structure.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is also used as a mechanism for storing timestamps in a number of file systems, file formats, and databases.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The C standard library uses Unix time for all date and time functions, and Unix time is sometimes referred to as time_t, the name of the data type used for timestamps in C and C++.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] C's Unix time functions are defined as the system time API in the POSIX specification.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The C standard library is used extensively in all modern desktop operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as macOS and Linux, where it is a standard programming interface.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] iOS provides a Swift API which defaults to using an epoch of 1 January 2001 but can also be used with Unix timestamps.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Android uses Unix time alongside a time zone for its system time API.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Windows does not use Unix time for storing time internally but does use it in system APIs, which are provided in C++ and implement the C standard library specification.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is used in the PE format for Windows executables.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is typically available in major programming languages and is widely used in desktop, mobile, and web application programming.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Java provides an Instant object which holds a Unix timestamp in both seconds and nanoseconds.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Python provides a time library which uses Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] JavaScript provides a Date library which provides and stores timestamps in milliseconds since the Unix epoch and is implemented in all modern desktop and mobile web browsers as well as in JavaScript server environments like Node.js.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Free Pascal implements UNIX time with the GetTickCount (deprecated unsigned 32 bit) and GetTickCount64 (Unsigned 64 bit) functions to a resolution of 1ms on Unix-like platforms.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Filesystems designed for use with Unix-based operating systems tend to use Unix time.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] APFS, the file system used by default across all Apple devices, and ext4, which is widely used on Linux and Android devices, both use Unix time in nanoseconds for file timestamps.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Several archive file formats can store timestamps in Unix time, including RAR and tar.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is also commonly used to store timestamps in databases, including in MySQL and PostgreSQL.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time was designed to encode calendar dates and times in a compact manner intended for use by computers internally.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] It is not intended to be easily read by humans or to store time-zone-dependent values.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] It is also limited by default to representing time in seconds, making it unsuited for use when a more precise measurement of time is needed, such as when measuring the execution time of programs.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time by design does not require a specific size for the storage, but most common implementations of Unix time use a signed integer with the same size as the word size of the underlying hardware.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] As the majority of modern computers are 32-bit or 64-bit, and a large number of programs are still written in 32-bit compatibility mode, this means that many programs using Unix time are using signed 32-bit integer fields.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The maximum value of a signed 32-bit integer is 231 − 1, and the minimum value is −231, making it impossible to represent dates before 13 December 1901 (at 20:45:52 UTC) or after 19 January 2038 (at 03:14:07 UTC).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The early cutoff can have an impact on databases that are storing historical information; in some databases where 32-bit Unix time is used for timestamps, it may be necessary to store time in a different form of field, such as a string, to represent dates before 1901.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The late cutoff is known as the Year 2038 problem and has the potential to cause issues as the date approaches, as dates beyond the 2038 cutoff would wrap back around to the start of the representable range in 1901.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Date range cutoffs are not an issue with 64-bit representations of Unix time, as the effective range of dates representable with Unix time stored in a signed 64-bit integer is over 584 billion years, or 292 billion years in either direction of the 1970 epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix time is not the only standard for time that counts away from an epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Windows epoch time is used to store timestamps for files and in protocols such as the Active Directory Time Service and Server Message Block.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The Network Time Protocol used to coordinate time between computers uses an epoch of 1 January 1900, counted in an unsigned 32-bit integer for seconds and another unsigned 32-bit integer for fractional seconds, which rolls over every 232 seconds (about once every 136 years).
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Many applications and programming languages provide methods for storing time with an explicit time zone.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] There are also a number of time format standards which exist to be readable by both humans and computers, such as ISO 8601.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Unix enthusiasts have a history of holding "time_t parties" (pronounced "time tea parties") to celebrate significant values of the Unix time number.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] These are directly analogous to the new year celebrations that occur at the change of year in many calendars.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] As the use of Unix time has spread, so has the practice of celebrating its milestones.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Usually it is time values that are round numbers in decimal that are celebrated, following the Unix convention of viewing `time_t` values in decimal.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Among some groups round binary numbers are also celebrated, such as +230, which occurred at 13:37:04 UTC on Saturday, 10 January 2004.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] Vernor Vinge's novel *A Deepness in the Sky* describes a spacefaring trading civilization thousands of years in the future that still uses the Unix epoch.
[src:dayjs-datetime/unix-time] The "programmer-archaeologist" responsible for finding and maintaining usable code in mature computer systems first believes that the epoch refers to the time when man first walked on the Moon, but then realizes that it is "the 0-second of one of humankind's first computer operating systems".
